To expand the main container of your application, you can modify the CSS styles applied to the container element. In your case, the main container is the `<div>` element with the class name `app` in the `App.js` file.

Here are a few ways you can expand the container:

1. Set a fixed height:
   - Open the `App.css` file (or the file where you have your CSS styles).
   - Add the following CSS rule:
     ```css
     .app {
       height: 100vh; /* This sets the height to 100% of the viewport height */
     }
     ```

2. Set a minimum height:
   - Open the `App.css` file.
   - Add the following CSS rule:
     ```css
     .app {
       min-height: 100vh; /* This sets the minimum height to 100% of the viewport height */
     }
     ```

3. Use flexbox to expand the container:
   - Open the `App.css` file.
   - Add the following CSS rules:
     ```css
     html, body, #root {
       height: 100%;
     }

     .app {
       display: flex;
       flex-direction: column;
       min-height: 100%;
     }
     ```
   - This sets the height of the `html`, `body`, and `#root` elements to 100% and uses flexbox to expand the `.app` container to fill the available height.

Make sure to adjust the styles based on your specific requirements and the existing styles in your application.

After making the necessary changes in the CSS file, the main container should expand vertically to fill the available space.

To expand the width of the main container, you can modify the CSS styles similarly to how we adjusted the height. Here are a few ways to control the width:

1. Set a fixed width:
   - Open the `App.css` file.
   - Add the following CSS rule:
     ```css
     .app {
       width: 800px; /* Set the desired fixed width */
       margin: 0 auto; /* Center the container horizontally */
     }
     ```

2. Set a percentage width:
   - Open the `App.css` file.
   - Add the following CSS rule:
     ```css
     .app {
       width: 80%; /* Set the width to a percentage of its parent container */
       margin: 0 auto; /* Center the container horizontally */
     }
     ```

3. Set a maximum width:
   - Open the `App.css` file.
   - Add the following CSS rule:
     ```css
     .app {
       max-width: 1200px; /* Set the maximum width of the container */
       margin: 0 auto; /* Center the container horizontally */
     }
     ```

4. Use flexbox to expand the container:
   - Open the `App.css` file.
   - Add the following CSS rules:
     ```css
     html, body, #root {
       height: 100%;
     }

     #root {
       display: flex;
       justify-content: center;
     }

     .app {
       flex-grow: 1;
       max-width: 1200px; /* Set the maximum width of the container */
     }
     ```
   - This sets the `#root` element to use flexbox and centers its children horizontally. The `.app` container is set to grow and fill the available width up to the specified `max-width`.

Choose the approach that best fits your desired layout and design. You can combine the height and width styles to achieve the desired size for your main container.

Remember to adjust the values (`800px`, `80%`, `1200px`) according to your specific requirements and the content of your application.

